Analytical Breakdown of The Premier League¶

A data driven journey exploring the trends in the biggest Footballing league in the world¶¶

By Praatyush Gupta and Harshpreet Singh Tuteja¶

Background and Motivation:¶

As avid fans of the beautiful game of football i.e. soccer our group decided to embark on a data driven journey to explore, anaylse, and apply our course knowledge to the Premier League.

To provide some backgroud knowledge about the Premium League and how it works: The Premier League is the highest level of the English football league system. Contested by 20 clubs, it operates on a system of promotion and relegation with the English Football League (EFL). Each team plays 38 matches: two against each other, one home and one away. The competition was founded as the FA Premier League on 20 February 1992 since then the Premier League has become the most-watched football league(in terms of viewships) and the richest football league(in terms of media rights, sponsorship, and revenue) in the world. Note: The Premium Leauge was founded in the year 1992 after deciding to break away from English Football Leauge, which it was a part of since the year 1888. For the purpose of this project, we have only considered data after the year 1992 and have therefore haven't used data dating back to the English Football League.

For those interested in a deeper understanding abou the history of the league, we would recommend the following resources to take a look at:

https://www.premierleague.com/history/origins

https://www.footballhistory.org/league/premier-league.html

https://www.premierleague.com/premier-league-explained

Through the means of this project we aim to utilise data in order to btter understand the league. Try understanding historical patterns, try to make predictions based on the data available and thus take a more structured and data driven approach allowing us to better quantify the league. Throughout our project we will take a look who the winners of the Premier League are, who the runners up have been, what has been the historic performances of the teams, the number of red and yellow cards given through each season, finding whether there is any corelation between the number of foul violations and the winners? To find the answers to all such questions, read along!!!

data = []

        break

    df['season'] = val.text
    data.append(df)

main = pd.concat(data)
main.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
main

Web Data Extraction:¶

For this project, all our data has been scrapped from the following website: https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/t/t.html?cat=eng. To help us scrape data we have made use of the beautifulsoup library in python. After retriving the data from the HTML page, we have stored the scraped data into a Pandas DataFrame to help us organise, store and process the data.

Data Cleaning:¶

According to tableau.com, Data cleaning is the process of fixing or removing incorrect, corrupted, incorrectly formatted, duplicate, or incomplete data within a dataset. This was an essential stage of our projetc which allowed us to transfrom raw data which we can further anaylse to gain meaninful insights from.

After storing our data into a Pandas DataFrame there were several columns which were out of scope for the purpose of our project. Several columns also lacked meaningful column names whcih made it difficult for us to anaylse our dataset and hence we first dropped all the non essential coloums, we then proceeded to rename the column names for them to tell us what data they represented.

Removing unwanted data from our dataset helps us get rid of any irrelevant information that isn't specifically related to our focus. Irrelevant observations that don't align with our specific analysis can distract from our main goal, which is to gain insights into certain aspects of the English Premier League.

We then removed all columns which contained data filled with NaN entries since we could not have utilised them for the purpose of this project. Next, we removed unwanted information and any duplicate data by searching for the .unique() values. Next, we converted certain columns of the dataset to a format that made the values easier to read. For instance, we ensured we identified only the unique season years and used the format '2021-22' for the season.

After cleaning the data, we obtained a Pandas DataFrame that enables us to perform the necessary transformations to draw the conclusions we seek. This DataFrame includes information about the winners and runner-ups of the English Premier League, the number of teams in the league per season, the evolution of the number of leagues, historical team performances, and the number of yellow and red cards issued from 1992 to 2023.

English Premier League Winners:¶

To find our winners from our DataFrame, we made use of df scores which we then filtered by rows in which rank = 1. This allowed us to see all the winners of the Premium League (as is also shown using the graph below) starting from 1992. We can see that throughout the history of the league, Manchester United is the most successful team, winning the competition a record 13 times.

Manchester City comes second in terms of the number of league titles won. We can futher see that Chelsea has won five times, placing them in third. Arsenal has won four times, putting them in fourth. Liverpool, Leicester, and Blackburn Rovers have each won once, tying them for fifth, sixth, and seventh places.

Total Number of Seasons each team has been in the First Division:¶

Since the Premier League uses a system of promotion and relegation we wanted to see which are the teams which have had a consistent historic performance and have been in the top tier of English Football the longest. In order to do so, we produced a bar chart and arranged the data in ascending order to illustrate the duration each team has spent in the top division of the league. Liverpool and Manchester United share the top position, having spent the longest time in the First Division. Following them, Arsenal holds third place, with Chelsea in fourth.

The Number of Red Cards Per Season:¶

We conducted a groupby() operation on the seasons and tallied the occurrences of red cards issued each season. One prominent peak was observed between the seasons 2002-2003 and 2007-2008, during which the highest number of red cards were issued. Moreover, the inaugural season from 1993-1994 appeared to have the fewest instances of red cards handed out.

The number of Yellow Cards Per Season:¶

We utilized a groupby() function on the seasons once more, this time focusing on YC (yellow cards) instead of RD (red cards), enabling us to specifically examine the count of yellow cards per season. Two distinct peaks were evident: one spanning from the seasons 1997-1998 to 2002-2003, and another from the seasons 2012-2013 to 2017-2018, during which the highest numbers of yellow cards were recorded.

Fairplay:¶

We generated a chart illustrating the inverse of the maximum number of violations per team, assigning 2 points for red cards and 1 point for yellow cards. We then deducted this score from the total number of violations to compute the Fairplay score. Swidon Town emerged with the highest Fairplay score, followed by Blackpool in second place.

In [146]:
unfair = (main.groupby('Team_Name').sum().YC) + 2*(main.groupby('Team_Name').sum().YC) 
highest = unfair.max()
fp = unfair.apply(lambda x : highest-x ).sort_values(ascending = False).rename("fp")
fp.plot(kind='bar', color='black', figsize=(15,5))
plt.title('Overall Fairplay Score by Team')
plt.xlabel('Teams')
plt.ylabel('Fairplay Score')
Out[146]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Fairplay Score')

Regression¶

To test our hypothesis that the number of times a league is in the first divison is linearly related to the team's average Goal difference and it's Fairplay, we first created a table for the teams' avg GD (Goal Difference)

We then created a multiple linear regression with Number of times in the First division as the response variable and the the GD and Fairplay score as our explanatory variables.

Lets break down what each of these numbers means:

Intercept Value: The intercept represents the estimated average value of our dependent variable when all independent variables are zero. In our case, this indicates that if a team has a fairplay score of 0 and a goal difference of 0, they are expected to be in the first division about 15 times.

Coefficients: We have two coefficients for the Fairplay and Goal Difference (GD) variables. These coefficients indicate the relationship between each independent variable and the dependent variable. Specifically:

A 1-unit increase in the Fairplay score is associated with an approximate decrease of 0.002 in the average number of times a team is in the first division.

A 1-unit increase in the Goal Difference score is associated with an approximate increase of 0.43 in the average number of times a team is in the first division.
